 harassing experience that understandably seared the boy's memory. The sketch moves on to a host of details about antebellum Hannibal, its society and its attitudes toward slavery, and to vivid memories about the child, his mother, and his father in the 1840's and 1850's. The movement from a single remembered episode to a series of loosely associated recollections was a typical performance in Clemens's "autobiography" and his fiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 4aAmerican literature. 4aEnglish Literature. 4acollections. 4afiction. 4aliterary collections. 4aliterary studies. 4aliterature. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh1 aBlair, Walter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052037571040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520375710423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520375710/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles